Note:
Runa Standard Library: Complex Number Mathematics

Production-grade complex number implementation with comprehensive mathematical operations,
polar form conversions, and advanced complex analysis functions.
:End Note

Import "math/core" as Core

Note: Complex Number Type
Type called "ComplexNumber":
    real as Number
    imaginary as Number

Note: Construction Functions
Process called "create_complex" that takes real as Number and imaginary as Number returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as real
    imaginary as imaginary

Process called "create_complex_polar" that takes magnitude as Number and angle as Number returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as magnitude multiplied by Core.cos with angle as angle
    imaginary as magnitude multiplied by Core.sin with angle as angle

Process called "create_complex_from_real" that takes real as Number returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as real
    imaginary as 0

Note: Basic Properties
Process called "get_magnitude" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns Number:
    Return Core.sqrt with x as z.real multiplied by z.real z.imaginary multiplied by z.imaginary

Process called "get_argument" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns Number:
    Return Core.atan2 with y as z.imaginary and x as z.real

Process called "get_conjugate" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as z.real
    imaginary as negative z.imaginary

Process called "get_reciprocal" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let magnitude_squared be z.real multiplied by z.real z.imaginary multiplied by z.imaginary
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as z.real divided by magnitude_squared
    imaginary as negative z.imaginary divided by magnitude_squared

Note: Basic Arithmetic
Process called "add_complex" that takes a as ComplexNumber and b as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as a.real b.real
    imaginary as a.imaginary b.imaginary

Process called "subtract_complex" that takes a as ComplexNumber and b as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as a.real - b.real
    imaginary as a.imaginary - b.imaginary

Process called "multiply_complex" that takes a as ComplexNumber and b as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as a.real multiplied by b.real - a.imaginary multiplied by b.imaginary
    imaginary as a.real multiplied by b.imaginary a.imaginary multiplied by b.real

Process called "divide_complex" that takes a as ComplexNumber and b as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let denominator be b.real multiplied by b.real b.imaginary multiplied by b.imaginary
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as a.real multiplied by b.real a.imaginary multiplied by b.imaginary divided by denominator
    imaginary as a.imaginary multiplied by b.real - a.real multiplied by b.imaginary divided by denominator

Process called "multiply_by_scalar" that takes z as ComplexNumber and scalar as Number returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as z.real multiplied by scalar
    imaginary as z.imaginary multiplied by scalar

Note: Powers and Roots
Process called "power_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber and n as Number returns ComplexNumber:
    Let r be get_magnitude with z as z
    Let theta be get_argument with z as z
    Let new_r be Core.power with base as r and exponent as n
    Let new_theta be theta multiplied by n
    Return create_complex_polar with magnitude as new_r and angle as new_theta

Process called "sqrt_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let r be get_magnitude with z as z
    Let theta be get_argument with z as z
    Let new_r be Core.sqrt with x as r
    Let new_theta be theta divided by 2
    Return create_complex_polar with magnitude as new_r and angle as new_theta

Process called "nth_root_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber and n as Integer returns List[ComplexNumber]:
    Let r be get_magnitude with z as z
    Let theta be get_argument with z as z
    Let new_r be Core.nth_root with x as r and n as n
    Let roots be List.new
    For k from 0 to n - 1:
    Let new_theta be theta 2 multiplied by Core.pi multiplied by k divided by n
    Let root be create_complex_polar with magnitude as new_r and angle as new_theta
    List.add with lst as roots and item as root
    Return roots

Note: Exponential and Logarithmic Functions
Process called "exp_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let exp_real be Core.exp with x as z.real
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as exp_real multiplied by Core.cos with angle as z.imaginary
    imaginary as exp_real multiplied by Core.sin with angle as z.imaginary

Process called "log_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let r be get_magnitude with z as z
    Let theta be get_argument with z as z
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as Core.log with x as r
    imaginary as theta

Process called "log10_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let natural_log be log_complex with z as z
    Let ln10 be Core.log with x as 10
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as natural_log.real divided by ln10
    imaginary as natural_log.imaginary divided by ln10

Note: Trigonometric Functions
Process called "sin_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as Core.sin with angle as z.real multiplied by Core.cosh with x as z.imaginary
    imaginary as Core.cos with angle as z.real multiplied by Core.sinh with x as z.imaginary

Process called "cos_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as Core.cos with angle as z.real multiplied by Core.cosh with x as z.imaginary
    imaginary as negative Core.sin with angle as z.real multiplied by Core.sinh with x as z.imaginary

Process called "tan_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let sin_z be sin_complex with z as z
    Let cos_z be cos_complex with z as z
    Return divide_complex with a as sin_z and b as cos_z

Note: Hyperbolic Functions
Process called "sinh_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as Core.sinh with x as z.real multiplied by Core.cos with angle as z.imaginary
    imaginary as Core.cosh with x as z.real multiplied by Core.sin with angle as z.imaginary

Process called "cosh_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Return ComplexNumber with:
    real as Core.cosh with x as z.real multiplied by Core.cos with angle as z.imaginary
    imaginary as Core.sinh with x as z.real multiplied by Core.sin with angle as z.imaginary

Process called "tanh_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns ComplexNumber:
    Let sinh_z be sinh_complex with z as z
    Let cosh_z be cosh_complex with z as z
    Return divide_complex with a as sinh_z and b as cosh_z

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "is_real" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns Boolean:
    Return Core.abs with x as z.imaginary is less than 1e-15

Process called "is_pure_imaginary" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns Boolean:
    Return Core.abs with x as z.real is less than 1e-15

Process called "is_zero" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns Boolean:
    Return Core.abs with x as z.real is less than 1e-15 and Core.abs with x as z.imaginary is less than 1e-15

Process called "are_equal" that takes a as ComplexNumber and b as ComplexNumber and tolerance as Number returns Boolean:
    Let real_diff be Core.abs with x as a.real - b.real
    Let imag_diff be Core.abs with x as a.imaginary - b.imaginary
    Return real_diff is less than tolerance and imag_diff is less than tolerance

Process called "format_complex" that takes z as ComplexNumber returns String:
    If is_zero with z as z:
    Return "0"
    If is_real with z as z:
    Return String.format with template as "{}" and args as [z.real]
    If is_pure_imaginary with z as z:
    If z.imaginary is equal to 1:
    Return "i"
    If z.imaginary is equal to -1:
    Return "-i"
    Return String.format with template as "{}i" and args as [z.imaginary]
    If z.imaginary is greater than 0:
    Return String.format with template as "{} + {}i" and args as [z.real, z.imaginary]
    Return String.format with template as "{} minus {}i" and args as [z.real, Core.abs with x as z.imaginary]